  "id": "glycine-serine-threonine-metabolism",
  "name": "Glycine, serine and threonine metabolism",
  "category": "amino-acid-metabolism",
  "summary": "Interconversion and catabolism of the three-carbon amino-acid family — de novo serine synthesis from the glycolytic intermediate 3-phosphoglycerate, the serine↔glycine one-carbon shuttle, the glycine cleavage system, threonine breakdown, and the choline/betaine/sarcosine oxidative-demethylation arm.",
  "description": "This module (KEGG map00260) is the metabolic hub that links central carbon metabolism to one-carbon (folate) metabolism, the methionine/SAM cycle, and dozens of biosynthetic sinks (purines, heme, glutathione, creatine, phospholipids, sphingolipids). **Serine** is made de novo by the phosphorylated pathway: PHGDH oxidizes the glycolytic intermediate 3-phosphoglycerate to 3-phosphohydroxypyruvate (the committed, rate-limiting step), PSAT1 transaminates it to phosphoserine, and PSPH hydrolyzes the phosphate to give L-serine. Serine and **glycine** are freely interconverted by serine hydroxymethyltransferase (cytosolic SHMT1, mitochondrial SHMT2), which transfers serine's β-carbon to tetrahydrofolate as 5,10-methylene-THF — the entry point for the folate one-carbon pool. The mitochondrial **glycine cleavage system** (a four-protein complex: GLDC/P, GCSH/H, AMT/T, DLD/L) oxidatively decarboxylates glycine to a second 5,10-methylene-THF plus CO2 and NH3; its loss causes nonketotic hyperglycinemia (glycine encephalopathy). **Threonine** is catabolized mainly by serine/threonine dehydratase (SDS) to 2-oxobutanoate (→ propionyl-CoA); a minor threonine-aldolase side activity of SHMT1 yields glycine + acetaldehyde. The classic TDH→GCAT route to glycine + acetyl-CoA is essentially inactive in humans because threonine 3-dehydrogenase (TDH) is a pseudogene. The **choline oxidation** arm (CHDH → betaine aldehyde → betaine by ALDH7A1) feeds BHMT, which remethylates homocysteine to methionine; betaine is then demethylated stepwise (DMGDH → sarcosine → SARDH → glycine), each step donating a one-carbon unit to THF. Additional branches: GNMT methylates glycine to sarcosine using SAM (buffering cellular methylation capacity), peroxisomal AGT detoxifies glyoxylate to glycine (its deficiency causes primary hyperoxaluria type 1), and serine racemase makes D-serine, the NMDA-receptor co-agonist. The serine synthesis pathway is transcriptionally amplified in many cancers (PHGDH amplification; ATF4/NRF2 control), making this a prominent 'cancer rewiring' node.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["ubiquitous", "liver", "kidney", "brain", "erythrocyte", "proliferating tissue"],
